    momData.put(6, [
      "<p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At week six, your breasts are getting ready to breastfeed, which is wonderful! You might experience breast changes, including areola darkening, soreness, and swelling.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Frequent urination happens when your bladder pushes on your developing uterus. By leaning forward while urinating, you can reduce the frequency of bathroom trips and ensure that your bladder is fully cleared every time.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Morning sickness is another symptom. The reason for this is a rise in the pregnancy hormone, hCG. Anytime during the day, it can happen. See your doctor if vomiting makes it difficult for you to eat.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week, your baby's mouth, ears, and nose begin to form. Your baby's heart isn't fully developed, but its heart tube is beating fast, about 160 times a minute. Baby's intestines and lungs are also developing this week.&nbsp;</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Immunity During Pregnancy</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The immune system often weakens during pregnancy, especially from weeks 6 to 8, when most of your baby's organs are still developing.</span></p> <ul> <li><strong><span style='font-weight: 400;'>To boost your immune system, eat a healthy diet and take daily vitamins according to instructions by your doctor.&nbsp;</span></strong></li> </ul> <ul> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Look for medication that contains vitamin C, which boosts immunity.</span></li> </ul> <ul> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Maintain a light exercise routine, but don't forget to get enough sleep as well, both can help to reduce stress and strengthen immunity.</span></li> </ul> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Week 6 Care Tips | Toxicosis</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Most of the time, pregnancy nausea and vomiting are called pregnancy vomiting or even toxicosis. It is not a widely used reference for pregnancy's early symptoms.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>By definition, toxicosis is a poisoning-related condition. However, medical professionals avoid using this word because it can be misleading. Certain foods may naturally make your body react negatively to them, marking them as 'poisons.' Your body uses this natural process to alert you when any medicines are unnecessary. Even your unborn child might get harmed by some of these.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Remember that the next time you vomit, it's your body trying to get rid of anything it doesn't want.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>To avoid such things, Eat little but often, get lots of rest, be aware of the risk of UTIs, and avoid coloring your hair. Contact your doctor if you are unable to consume any food or liquids for six hours.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Take Healthy Diet</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Eating well during pregnancy is key for an easy and happy delivery! But during this week, things could get a little complicated because simply thinking of an egg, a chicken, or any other food high in protein from poultry could make you feel nauseous or even vomit. So, you should consider </span><strong>Zinc</strong><span style='font-weight: 400;'>.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Zinc is necessary during pregnancy because it impacts cell formation. Zinc ensures rapid and strong development for your baby, since they begin as a little ball of cells.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Zinc also boosts quicker wound healing and strengthens immunity. It promotes weight gain and improves the way your baby's sense system develops. Your kid could be at risk for certain infections that you get because of low zinc levels.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>The food items contain zinc:</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- beans,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- nuts;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- whole grains,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- cereals;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- dairy;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- red meats,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- poultry,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- oysters.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Eat the meals you enjoy, and don't force yourself to consume anything. Your body can reject it, and you might be unable to keep it within.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Things to Avoid</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Smoking has severe negative health effects. When smoke circulates from the placenta to the unborn child during pregnancy, the danger increases. Smoking has been linked to miscarriage, stillbirth, placental abruption, preeclampsia, abrupt newborn death, pediatric malignancies, and behavioral issues.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>There isn't a single acceptable quantity of cigarettes to smoke. It's perfect to stop smoking now if you smoke.&nbsp;</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Avoid Caffeine</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Caffeine should be avoided during pregnancy because it can pass the placenta and impact fetal growth. Risks include low birth weight, premature birth, and developmental problems.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Avoiding caffeine during pregnancy can help produce better results.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Help your baby to be healthy by avoiding such things!</span></p>"
    ]);
    momData.put(7, ["<h2><strong>First Trimester: What to Expect?</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Are you worried about not gaining weight during the first trimester? You shouldn't worry about this because pregnancy does not show any weight gain this week. In fact, many mothers who have frequent nausea and vomiting may be losing a little weight. (every women experiences differ)</span></p> <p>Your baby bump will take some time to appear. If you carry twins or more babies, your belly may appear earlier than the standard time.</p> <p>During this week, your baby's soft bones begin to form. Your baby now has eyelids, but they remain closed.&nbsp;</p> <p>Your baby's size will grow like lime in the first trimester, so avoid high caloric consumption. You just need to eat nutrient-dense food that is high in nutrients but relatively low in calories.</p> <p>Eat extra fruits, vegetables, and foods high in protein, such as lean meats and tofu, for as long as your stomach will allow. Limiting junk food and sugary drinks is also effective.</p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>&nbsp;</span></p> <h2><strong>Diet Tip</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your baby is tiny this week and will take from your body what it needs to grow and develop. So, you should supply your body and baby with the best nutrition.</span></p> <ul> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Pregnancy diets must include equal green, red, yellow, and orange vegetables. Eat three to five servings of veggies each day. Add fresh veggies like spinach, broccoli, tomatoes, red peppers, pumpkin, carrots, yellow peppers, and corn to your diet.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Choose fresh fruit over canned or preserved meals, as the latter may contain bacteria that could be dangerous to you and the unborn child. Each day, you should eat three to four servings of fresh fruit.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During the day, drink six glasses of water minimum. Avoid soda because it will fill you up and add empty calories.</span></li> </ul> <h2><strong>Other Recommended Foods:-</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- oatmeal (helps decrease cholesterol)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- dry beans and lentils (protein, fiber)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- enriched breakfast cereal (folate)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- whole-grain bread (fiber, iron, and zinc)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- pasteurized dairy products (calcium)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- cheeses (calcium, protein) mozzarella and cheddar</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- eggs and soy products (protein)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- bananas (potassium)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- oranges (vitamin C, folate, and fiber)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- almonds and dried fruits (apricots, cherries, and cranberries)</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Fitness Tips</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>To be fit in the first trimester, all you need to do is relax. Avoid overly demanding activities and exercise at your own speed.</span></p> <p>Early morning walks are physically stimulating without being too demanding. For first trimester dizziness and morning sickness, you can also try stretching routines and deep breathing exercises.</p> <p>You should start Kegel exercises now. You can strengthen your perineal muscles with Kegel exercises.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Shopping Tips</strong></h2> <ul> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><strong>A Pregnancy Journal:</strong><span style='font-weight: 400;'> For storing your thoughts and feelings during your pregnancy.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><strong>Suitable Lotions: </strong><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your skin may become drier than usual, so you can use safe and quality lotions or oils to hydrate it.</span></li> </ul> <p><strong>A Comfy Brassier: </strong><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Because your breasts are now sore and enlarged, it could be beneficial to wear cozy clothing.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
    momData.put(8, ["<h2><strong>The Uterus is as Big as an Orange.&nbsp;</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Congratulations! Your pregnancy is now eight weeks along! Your clothes may suddenly feel a little tight on your belly, even if your tiny baby is just the size of a raspberry:) That's because, before pregnancy, your uterus was around the size of your fist; now, it has enlarged to the size of an orange.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This week, diarrhea, bloating, gas, and morning sickness are possible. You will feel better in a few weeks, so don't worry. Just imagine the little miracle growing rapidly inside your uterus.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Morning Sickness</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Morning sickness occurs in pregnant women as early as week eight. The fact that not all women have it is fantastic news. You might not feel nauseous if you are one of the blessed few. But for the majority, this is a fairly common symptom that can occur at any time of day, not just in the morning. It may continue for a minute or the entire day.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Pregnancy hormone levels rise quickly, which results in nausea. Once the embryo begins to implant into the uterine lining, it produces it. Most women start to feel better by weeks 12 and 14.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>Advice for feeling better:</strong></p> <ul> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Eat one or two dry crackers in the morning;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>eat little meals every two hours;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>eat food that contains ginger;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>inhale the aroma of lemon zest;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>eat yogurt;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>eat dry foods like mashed potatoes or plain rice;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>sip water throughout the day;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>and stay away from tea, coffee, and soda.</span></li> </ul> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Pregnancy-related nausea and vomiting are quite common, but if you aren't able to eat or drink for more than six hours, consult with your doctor.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Antiemetic sea band</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Irritability and vomiting still not easing? Not a problem! An anti-nausea sea band works when everything else fails. It is affordable, painless, safe, and simple to use.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Sea bands that reduce nausea function by applying acupressure. The acupressure technique of sea bands makes use of the numerous pressure points on the wrist, which can be used to relieve nausea and vomiting.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Similar to an arm band! Just tie it around your wrist and see the results. You can use this at any time of day or whenever you get your worst spell of nausea. You can wear this before sleep if you are suffering from morning sickness.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You can use this even after your pregnancy to ease any nausea or vomiting.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Eat Calcium For Your Baby</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You should get sufficient calcium to properly grow your unborn baby's heart, brain, muscles, bones, and teeth.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>If you don't consume enough calcium from food or a prenatal vitamin, your baby will feed off your calcium reserves.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Calcium is present in the following foods:</span></p> <ul> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Calcium is present in the following foods:</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>pasteurized dairy products like milk,&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>hard cheeses, yogurt, and butter;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>seafood like shrimp, sardines, and salmon;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>dark green leafy vegetables like kale, spinach, and turnip greens;&nbsp;</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>and beverages with added calcium such soy milk and orange juice.</span></li> </ul> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>When pregnant, is X-ray safe?</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Teeth, arms, legs, and chest X-rays are safe because they do not show your reproductive organs. To protect your uterus, a leaded collar and apron may be worn during abdomen and lower back procedures.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Although there is a possibility that the X-ray process will harm your unborn child, research indicates that this is likely because the radiation dose is so minimal. It may sound unsettling; X-rays during pregnancy may be conducted if necessary for medical reasons. This is advised only if the advantages exceed the risks.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your doctor will suggest safe methods at every step, so you don't need to worry. Have a safe and healthy pregnancy, and cherish every minute and tiny change!</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
    momData.put(9, ["<h2><strong>9 Weeks Pregnant &ndash; What to Expect</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Congratulations! Your pregnancy is nine weeks along. This is the time when your child develops into a foetus and finishes the embryonic stage. At this point, your baby starts looking like a human being rather than a seed in a pod!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>As your baby transforms from an embryo to a fetus, you begin to notice a number of changes. Your weight won't change greatly this week, though some women may lose weight as a result of sickness or having a tendency to throw up. You may also experience heartburn, bloatedness, and mood swings. It is better to drink a lot of water during this time!</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Heartburn During Week 9</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Heartburn, also known as acid reflux, is a burning sensation in the chest that usually occurs after eating.</span></p> <p><strong>Advice for treating heartburn:</strong></p> <ol> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Consume small meals often. Eat 5&ndash;6 small meals a day instead of 3 large ones.</span></li> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Steer clear of oily and spicy foods. Foods that are fried, oily, or spicy may cause reflux.</span></li> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Avoid lying down after eating. Sitting up straight helps with quicker food absorption.</span></li> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>See your doctor if you still have heartburn so they will give you antacids that are safe for pregnancy.</span></li> </ol> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Mood Swings</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Pregnancy-related mood swings are very common. You could experience multiple emotions at once, such as confidence, fear, anger, and happiness. During pregnancy, particularly in the first and third trimesters, hormones can intensify your feelings.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>Advice for Mood Swings:</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- start walking</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- be physically active;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- minimize stress;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- get enough sleep;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- drink enough of water;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- eat healthily and don't skip meals;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Speak with a friend or member of your family; Engage in soothing hobbies, such as pregnancy yoga</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Diet Tips | Vitamins</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your little one is growing fast, but there is still a long way to go. With over 26 billion cells in your baby at birth, just think of the work your body goes through in nine months.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>This is when vitamin E becomes important. It helps in the formation of new cells and protects the cell walls that are essential to the growth of your little one. It also reduces the formation of stretch marks and supports healthy skin.</span></p> <p><strong>Vitamin E is available from the following sources:</strong></p> <ol> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Leafy greens, such as broccoli and spinach.</span></li> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Nuts and seeds, such as sunflower and peanut seeds.</span></li> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'> Vegetable oils, such as corn, soybean, and sunflower oil.</span></li> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Fortified spreads, cereals, and drinks.</span></li> </ol> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Things to Avoid</strong></h2> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <ul> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Don't expose yourself to dangerous environments like radiation, as it could harm the baby.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Stop heavy exercise routines because it could dehydrate you or divert your uterus' blood flow.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Caffeine can cause insomnia, so avoid it.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Products containing raw milk and unpasteurized milk should be stopped, as they may transmit diseases.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Avoid hot tubs (You should keep your baby's body temperature under 102 F (39 C). Staying in a hot tub may be harmful to your health.</span></li> </ul> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
    momData.put(10, ["<h2><strong>Week 10 Body Changes</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Hi there, baby bump! Now that you're ten weeks along, you can stop worrying about when your baby bump will appear because it will start growing this week! By week 10, your uterus has now grown to the size of a grapefruit, and you're getting closer to finishing the first trimester. You are feeling bloated (puffy) at this time.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Reduced blood sugar can lead to headaches, which increase symptoms of nausea and vomiting, especially during the first trimester.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your breasts will also appear to grow slightly, and as your pregnancy goes on, the bluish veins will show more clearly. This will get you ready for the important duty of breastfeeding your child.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Moreover, you might notice that your nails are growing faster and your hair becomes thicker. This is because of the estrogen hormone and the nutrients you get from food and supplements.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Ways to Stop Bloating</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Changing your diet can help with digestive problems, including snorting and bloating. Avoid eating late at night and try to cook six small meals each day.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Drink plenty of water, eat slowly, and avoid smoking and drinking alcohol. After eating, have a little walk. Some individuals find their bloating increase after consuming coffee or rich, fatty, and spicy foods. So, avoid consuming such things.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Protein at Week 10</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Protein is the nutrient that both you and the baby's cells require to grow. During pregnancy, you should consume sufficient protein, especially during the second and third trimesters when the baby is growing quickly.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Protein boosts the immune system, helps in the healing of infections, and gives new mothers energy. In order to prevent diabetes, a high-protein diet also maintains blood sugar.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong><em>Eat the following to get adequate protein:</em></strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Soybeans and tofu&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Nuts and seeds</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Pasteurized milk</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Cheese, and yogurt</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Eggs</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Lean meats</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Poultry, and fish</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Yoga</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Both yoga and meditation can help you maintain your body's flexibility and control your blood pressure. By doing this, you feel calm and sleep well.</span></p> <p><strong>Yoga helps you to:-</strong></p> <ul> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Connect with your feelings</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Stay focused</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Connect with your child</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Feel better about the way your body is changing.</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Feel peaceful and at ease</span></li> <li style='font-weight: 400;'><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Mentally get ready for birth and beyond.</span></li> </ul> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
    momData.put(11, ["<h2><strong>Your Pregnancy at Week 11</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During week 11 of pregnancy,&nbsp; you're in month 3 of your pregnancy. Your body has seen changes such as a rounder structure and more sensitive breasts, etc. You can experience more cravings for food as your morning sickness begins to fade.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At this time, you could feel so exhausted that all you want to do is lie down and go to sleep. Rest as much as you can; your body is working hard to take care of your growing child.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Now, your baby&rsquo;s cute facial development continues and the heart is fully formed.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Tips for Care of Your Skin</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During pregnancy, the skin stretches so much that stretch marks appear. They usually appear in areas of fat such as the arms, breasts, thighs, hips, and belly.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Is there any way to avoid stretch marks? Yes, here are some ways</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Staying hydrated</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>A stretch mark is caused by moisture loss in the skin. So, you should restore the moisture loss. Apply essential oils to the afflicted areas regularly. Sunflower, almond, argan, or avocado oils are found in most goods.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>Avoid scratching</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The skin may itch because of stretching. Do not scratch it, especially if the skin looks dark. Wear cotton clothing in place of wool, and apply extra oil to itchy areas.&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong>Use anti-stretch mark products</strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Don't stress out if you have stretch marks. Anti-stretch mark solutions can keep your skin flexible. Use them frequently, after delivery and during pregnancy. The marks may fade more quickly.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Nails and Hair During Pregnancy</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Did you not cut your fingernails two days ago? Does it seem like you have thicker hair than usual? It is obvious that the growth of your nails and hair is very fast. Why? Hormones involved in pregnancy!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During pregnancy, estrogen levels rise. This boosts nail growth and changes the texture of hair. Pregnancy's effects on metabolism and increased blood circulation supply the skin and connective tissues with extra nutrients.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Are you unhappy about the swelling in your hands when you are pregnant? You will at least have gorgeous nails!</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <h2><strong>Thiamine</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Thiamin, or vitamin B1, is an essential element to have all over pregnancy. It helps create fat and enables the normal functioning of amino acids.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Thiamin also controls the neurological system. A lack of vitamin B1 causes muscle weakness, fatigue, and nausea. When thiamin is present, tissues and cells have more energy, which is why this vitamin is crucial for pregnant women.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><strong><em>Eat the following to get adequate thiamin:-</em></strong></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Whole grains,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- rice, pasta,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- beans,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- almonds,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- berries,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- and fortified foods (Sunflower seeds, Yogurt etc)</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Shopping Advice!</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Being pregnant does not mean you cannot be fashionable. So, Let&rsquo;s do some shopping. Buy good, stretchy bras, maternity clothes, and stretchy pants, preferably in cotton. Buy vitamins and dietary supplements that your doctor recommends. Buy cozy shoes that will reduce swelling and cramping in the legs.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>The good news is that a healthy diet and comfortable clothes can go a long way toward ensuring comfort and maintaining a nutritious diet.<br /><br /></span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
    momData.put(12, ["<h2><strong>You at 12 weeks pregnant</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>It's exciting, ladies, that the first trimester is almost over! Your hormones that had gone crazy might be coming back to normal now.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>As your uterus begins to grow from your pelvis, pressure is released on your bladder, which lessens your need to urinate. This is excellent news. Additionally, you'll notice that your breasts get more sensitive and that the nausea and vomiting start to decrease.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your face and neck may have darker areas of skin. This is known as the 'mask of pregnancy' or 'chloasma.'&nbsp;</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Mask of Pregnancy</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Dark patches on your forehead, upper lip, and cheeks are a sign of chloasma, also known as Melasma. 50-75% of expectant mothers suffer from this type of Melasma.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h3><strong>Causes of Its? Estrogen!</strong></h3> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Hyperpigmentation is caused by an increase in estrogen levels this week. It is possible for stretch marks and the black vertical line known as the linea nigra to appear along your belly in addition to chloasma.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>There is good news: Your hyperpigmentation will worsen after giving birth.</span></p> <h2><strong>Safe Treatment</strong></h2> <ol> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Stay away from sun rays</span></li> </ol> <ol start='2'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'> Wear sunscreen</span></li> </ol> <ol start='3'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'> Use accurate skin care products</span></li> </ol> <ol start='4'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Try at-home masks and techniques&nbsp;</span></li> </ol> <ol start='5'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Consult your doctor.</span></li> </ol> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Care Tips</strong></h2> <ol> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>To maintain control over your blood sugar, eat often. But be careful not to overeat.</span></li> </ol> <ol start='2'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Maintaining a high-fiber diet is crucial. (Grains, raspberries, green peas, spinach, etc.)</span></li> </ol> <ol start='3'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'> Drink at least 8 glasses of water daily</span></li> </ol> <ol start='4'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Walking for 15 to 60 minutes a day. (Fruits with high water content include watermelon, apples, and oranges. Water is also included in spinach, cabbage, peppers, eggplant, and cauliflower.)</span></li> </ol> <ol start='5'> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Maintain good dental hygiene because hormones may be involved in gum bleeding.</span></li> </ol> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Bleeding Gums in Pregnancy</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Hormones cause your gums to swell and become sensitive, just like other pregnancy symptoms. It is natural for your gums to bleed a little bit when you wash your teeth, so don't be concerned by this.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Pregnancy-related bleeding of the gums can be avoided with these easy tips:</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- brush your teeth twice a day;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- use a toothbrush with smooth bristles;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Use a tongue scraper;&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- avoid sugary food;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- consult with your dentist</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Food You Need to Avoid Consuming</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- soft cheeses such as camembert or brie,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- raw fish,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- pate,&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- ready-made salads and cold delicatessen meats.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- Raw meat (most dangerous)</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>- unpasteurized juice.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>A nutritious diet is essential to maintaining fetal health and meeting the physical demands of pregnancy. Speak with your doctor about vitamins that will benefit both you and your baby!</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
    momData.put(13, ["<h2><strong>1st Trimester Completing</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Hello, mom-to-be. Congratulations! So, how do you feel that you are only several days away from the second trimester?</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Your uterus is now about the size of a big grapefruit and is beginning to grow from the base of your pelvis to the front of your belly.&nbsp;</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>At week 13, vaginal discharge increases. A thin, milky, mild-smelling discharge is normal during pregnancy. Vaginal discharge helps maintain good bacteria in the birth canal and protects it from infection.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You may experience dizziness this week. As progesterone increases blood flow to your baby, it decreases your own blood flow to your brain, leading to fainting spells. That's great for your baby, but not so great for you.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Low blood-sugar levels may cause dizziness if you're not eating regularly. So eat more frequently. If you feel dizzy, sit down right away, or lie down on the left side.</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Having Twins?</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Are you expecting twins? Maybe especially if you're older than 35 or if there is a family history of fraternal twins.</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <ul> <li><strong><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Finding out if you are pregnant with twins is only possible with an ultrasound scan.</span></strong></li> </ul> <ul> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Compared to a single pregnancy, physical changes during a twin pregnancy are more noticeable.</span></li> </ul> <ul> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Pregnancy health issues and complications are more common in women carrying twins.</span></li> </ul> <ul> <li><span style='font-weight: 400;'>For twin pregnancies, extra prenatal care, hospital delivery, good dietary guidance, and specialized medical attention are advised.</span></li> </ul> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Consult your practitioner at your next appointment to find out what's actually going on in there. You might actually have two babies in your womb, who knows?</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Ultrasound at Week 13</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Most pregnant women can get their first ultrasound this week. It's exciting to see your baby for the first time!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Transabdominal ultrasound requires a full bladder to visualize the baby properly. An ultrasound transabdominal uses gel on your belly and abdomen to capture detailed images of your baby and your womb.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>During the ultrasound, we'll measure your baby and listen to his heartbeat. A fast, galloping heartbeat is definitely music to your ears!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You will receive a copy of the first ultrasound report after the ultrasound. Remember to share your baby's first picture with your loved ones!</span></p> <h2>&nbsp;</h2> <h2><strong>Colostrum</strong></h2> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>You'll notice that your breasts become bigger and more sensitive as the first trimester comes to an end. The areas can get darker, and the bluish veins become more visible.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Breast milk is starting to form, one of the biggest changes this week. Colostrum leaks during this time, but you don't have to worry about it!</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Colostrum leaks contain a sticky yellowish-colored liquid. You can notice increased colostrum leakage around the end of your pregnancy. For now, simply focus on eating well so that when the time comes to start nursing, you will have enough milk to produce.</span></p> <p><span style='font-weight: 400;'>Remember that pregnancy can make you prone to infections, so you must be more careful about food hygiene. Whether you go to a restaurant or get street food, check that you're eating from a clean place!</span></p> <p>&nbsp;</p>"]);
